answers.body_markdown:
You have defined a your authentication type as **Basic Authentication** but you did not provide any bean to manage the **user** and the **password**. You can resolve it by:

 1. You don&#39;t have to define a type of authentication in your client
 2. If you choose **Basic Authentication** in your client, you have to define a **user** and **password**.

A sample code (don&#39;t use this in production):

    @Bean
    public InMemoryUserDetailsManager getUser() {
        return new InMemoryUserDetailsManager(
                User.withUsername(&quot;user&quot;)
                        .password(&quot;{noop}password&quot;)
                        .authorities(&quot;read&quot;)
                        .build()
        );
    }
    
    @Bean
    public PasswordEncoder getPasswordEncoder(){
        return NoOpPasswordEncoder.getInstance();
    }

