### Analysis

I&#39;ve done a test with your example (adding the missing getters/setters) and the result for me with MapStruct `1.4.2.Final` and `1.5.0.Beta2` is that the functionality works.
There is no infinite recursion with passing in a collection of size 2.

Below is the test that I have used for this:
```
    @Test
    void recursionTest() {
        MeshMapper mapper = Mappers.getMapper( MeshMapper.class );

        Mesh mesh1 = new Mesh();
        MeshColumn meshColumn1_1 = new MeshColumn();
        meshColumn1_1.setMesh( mesh1 );
        Mesh mesh2 = new Mesh();
        MeshColumn meshColumn1_2 = new MeshColumn();
        meshColumn1_2.setMesh( mesh2 );
        mesh1.setColumns( List.of( meshColumn1_1, meshColumn1_2 ) );
        MeshColumn meshColumn2 = new MeshColumn();
        meshColumn2.setMesh( mesh1 );
        mesh2.setColumns( List.of( meshColumn2 ) );

        List&lt;MeshDto&gt; listDto = mapper.toListDto( List.of( mesh1, mesh2 ), new CycleAvoidingMappingContext() );
        List&lt;Mesh&gt; listMesh = mapper.toListEntity( listDto, new CycleAvoidingMappingContext() );

        // prints out &#39;2&#39; and &#39;1&#39;. which is correct because mesh1 has 2 columns, and mesh2 has 1 column.
        listMesh.stream().map( mesh -&gt; mesh.getColumns().size() ).forEach( System.out::println );
    }
```

### Possible solution

One option that comes to mind is that your persistence layer is returning new objects every time. Since you are using an `IdentityHashMap`, the source must be the same object, and not equal to it. If you would change this into a normal `HashMap` and the equals are based on `Id`, then that might fix the problem.

For example: comparing `Mesh#1@123456` and `Mesh#1@654321` on being the same object would return `false`, while comparing `Mesh#1@123456` and `Mesh#1@654321` on being equal to each other would return `true`.

### Possible solution using a key instead of the source object in the hashmap.

```

public class CycleAvoidingMappingContext {

    private Map&lt;Key, Object&gt; knownInstances = new HashMap&lt;Key, Object&gt;();

    @Override
    @BeforeMapping
    public &lt;T&gt; T getMappedInstance(Object source, @TargetType Class&lt;T&gt; targetType) {

        T t = (T) knownInstances.get( toKey( source ) );
        return t;
    }

    @Override
    @BeforeMapping
    public void storeMappedInstance(Object source, @MappingTarget Object target) {
        knownInstances.put( toKey( source ), target );
    }

    private Key toKey(Object source) {
        if ( source instanceof AbstractEntity ) {
            Serializable id = ( (AbstractEntity&lt;?&gt;) source ).getId();
            return new Key( source, id );
        }
        return new Key( source, null );
    }

    private class Key {
        private Object source;
        private Serializable id;

        public Key(Object source, Serializable id) {
            this.source = source;
            this.id = id;
        }

        @Override
        public int hashCode() {
            return Objects.hash( source, id );
        }

        @Override
        public boolean equals(Object obj) {
            if (!(obj instanceof Key)) {
                return false;
            }
            if (id != null) {
                return Objects.equals( id, ( (Key) obj ).id )
                    &amp;&amp; Objects.equals( source.getClass(), ( (Key) obj ).source.getClass() );
            }else {
                if ( ( (Key) obj ).id != null ) {
                    return false;
                }
                else {
                    return Objects.equals( source.getClass(), ( (Key) obj ).source.getClass() );
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```
I&#39;ve tested this, you can find the test and source code I used here:

Root issue folder: https://github.com/Zegveld/mapstruct-sandbox/tree/main/infiniteMapping/eu.helral.mapstruct.sandbox.infiniteMapping

The `MeshMapperTest` contains 3 tests: 
 * A test showing that it would normally work.
 * A test showing that an infinite recursion variant does not work.
 * A test showing a solution for the infinite recursion variant.

The `FixedCycleAvoidingMappingContext` extends the `CycleAvoidingMappingContext` so that I did not have to duplicate the entire mapper as well for testing the fix.

# Solution
Create more DTO objects.

Currently you have the following input structure:

`Mesh` --&gt; `MeshColumn` --&gt; `Mesh`

You transform this into:

`MeshDto` --&gt; `MeshColumn` --&gt; `Mesh`

What you want is:

`MeshDto` --&gt; `MeshColumnDto` --&gt; `MeshDto`

So what you need to do is also create a `MeshColumnDto`, `MeshLineDto`, or exclude these from the mapping.

available since 1.5.0.Beta&#39;s:
Continuing on nested evaluations, you might even want to change the cyclic preventer into a @Condition method for all Mesh mappings, so that when you are about to map the same object it instead skips it.
See https://mapstruct.org/documentation/dev/reference/html/#conditional-mapping for more information.

# Problem description

What you want to prevent is:
MeshDto#1 --&gt; MeshColumnDto#2 --&gt; MeshDto#1 --&gt; MeshColumnDto#2 etc cyclic referencing.

# Solution

To prevent cyclic references you need to create an endpoint object to return instead of the actual object. Currently mapstruct just returns what it previously converted, but instead what you want is perhaps just the id of the item and no more information.

One option to achieve this is the following:
 1. add an interface to all your Dto&#39;s which has a method to create an endpoint object.
 2. whenever you find an already converted object, replace it with the endpoint object.

Example base interface:

```
interface BaseDto&lt;SELF&gt; {
    &lt;SELF&gt; createEndPointCopy();
}
```

example implementation:
```
MeshDto implements BaseDto&lt;MeshDto&gt; {
  // default stuff.
  @Override
  MeshDto createEndPointCopy() {
    MeshDto endpoint = new MeshDto();
    endpoint.setId(id);
    return endpoint;
  }
}
```

Next create the HierarchyEndingMappingContext

```
@Component
public class HierarchyEndingMappingContext {

    private Collection&lt;Object, BaseDto&lt;?&gt;&gt; knownInstances = new IdentityHashMap&lt;Object, BaseDto&lt;?&gt;&gt;();

    @BeforeMapping
    public &lt;T extends BaseDto&gt; T getMappedInstance(Object source, @TargetType Class&lt;T&gt; targetType) {
        T t = (T) knownInstances.get(source);
        return t != null ? t.createEndPointCopy() : null;
    }

    @BeforeMapping
    public void storeMappedInstance(Object source, @MappingTarget BaseDto target) {
        knownInstances.put( source, target );
    }
}
```

You might need to do some tweaking to have it respect hierarchies, because currently it will cause the following side effect when mapping a collection:
(A, B, C are instances, so A knows B, B knows C, and C knows B)
if I map collection `[A{B{C{B}}}, C{B}]`

we get as result: `[A{B{C{EndpointObject&lt;B&gt;}}}, EndpointObject&lt;C&gt;]`

while you might want to get: `[A{B{C{EndpointObject&lt;B&gt;}}}, C{B{EndpointObject&lt;C&gt;}}]`

# Important

All objects need to be mapped to be able to use this solution. So if you only have a MeshDto, but no MeshColumnDto then it will not work. You will need to have MeshDto refer to MeshColumnDto instead of MeshColumn, because otherwise you would just inherit the same MeshColumn object instead of one with the hierarchy cut off.

# Example repository

I&#39;ve added an example in the `remove.recursion` package of the following project: https://github.com/Zegveld/mapstruct-sandbox/tree/main/infiniteMapping/eu.helral.mapstruct.sandbox.infiniteMapping
There is also a test there that I used to confirm that it does indeed block the recursion.

