**Explanation:**

- `^` start of the string
- `\w` any word character (A-Z, a-z, 0-9, _).
- `$` end of the string

I have a similar issue with some event texts coming in.
They contain sometimes a similar UTF8 wording instead of normal ASCII characters..

You can make this visible by displaying the ord number for each:

           $splitted = mb_str_split($title);
               foreach ($splitted as $char) {
               echo mb_ord($char) . &#39; &#39;;
           }

This way you could also invalidate the characters of that range: &quot;Please use normal A-Z, ....&quot; etc

Another option would be to make a map of utf8=&gt;ascii characters and auto replace them.

See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_Alphanumeric_Symbols for a list of all of those in that range.

One example how this could work:
```php
&lt;?php

namespace App\Inflector;

class Utf8Decoder
{
    /**
     * @var array&lt;string&gt;
     */
    protected static array $charMap = [
        119808 =&gt; 65, // &#39;&#119808;&#39; - &#39;&#119833;&#39;
        119834 =&gt; 97, // &#39;&#119834;&#39; - &#39;&#119859;&#39;
        120276 =&gt; 65, // &#39;&#120276;&#39; =&gt; &#39;&#120301;&#39;,
        120302 =&gt; 97, // &#39;&#120302;&#39; =&gt; &#39;&#120327;&#39;,
    ];

    /**
     * @param string $string
     *
     * @return string
     */
    public static function decode(string $string): string
    {
        $charMap = static::charMap();

        $split = mb_str_split($string);
        foreach ($split as $k =&gt; $char) {
            $ord = mb_ord($char);

            if (!isset($charMap[$ord])) {
                continue;
            }

            $split[$k] = mb_chr($charMap[$ord]);
        }

        return implode(&#39;&#39;, $split);
    }

    /**
     * @return array&lt;string, string&gt;
     */
    protected static function charMap(): array
    {
        $charMap = [];

        foreach (static::$charMap as $k =&gt; $v) {
            for ($i = 0; $i &lt; 26; $i++) {
                $charMap[$k + $i] = $v + $i;
            }
