    String text1 = input.nextLine();
    System.out.print(&quot;Text2: &quot;);
    String text2 = input.nextLine();

That&#39;s because the [`Scanner.nextInt`](http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Scanner.html#nextInt%28%29) method does not read the *newline* character in your input created by hitting &quot;Enter,&quot; and so the call to [`Scanner.nextLine`](http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/util/Scanner.html#nextLine%28%29) returns after reading that *newline*.

You will encounter the similar behaviour when you use `Scanner.nextLine` after [`Scanner.next()`][2] or any `Scanner.nextFoo` method (except `nextLine` itself).

**Workaround:**

 - Either put a `Scanner.nextLine` call after each `Scanner.nextInt` or `Scanner.nextFoo` to consume rest of that line including *newline* 

        int option = input.nextInt();
        input.nextLine();  // Consume newline left-over
        String str1 = input.nextLine();

 - Or, even better, read the input through `Scanner.nextLine` and convert your input to the proper format you need. For example, you may convert to an integer using [`Integer.parseInt(String)`][1] method.

        int option = 0;
        try {
            option = Integer.parseInt(input.nextLine());
        } catch (NumberFormatException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
        String str1 = input.nextLine();



